[What "flaying / skinning" means: A method of slow and painful torture and/or execution in which skin is removed from the body. Generally, an attempt is made to keep the removed portion of skin intact.]
[What "brutalize / mutilation" means: The act of physically damaging or otherwise causing irreparable change and/or harm to a character, typically by the use of cutting, stabbing or contact objects; often exceptionally painful.]
[What "avulsion" means: An injury in which a body structure is torn/peeled off by either trauma or surgery. Most commonly refers to where all layers of the skin have been torn away, exposing the underlying structures (i.e., subcutaneous tissue, muscle, tendons, or bone). This is similar to an abrasion but more severe, as body parts such as an eyelid or an ear can be partially or fully detached from the body.]
81.name: Gore/Violence: Mutilation/Skinning

82.content:
[What "booby trap" means: A device or setup to kill, harm, immobilize, or surprise a victim.]
[What "bear trap" means: A pressure-activated metal trap with sharp edges. When the victim steps on the trap, two jaws with rows of metal teeth spring up into the victim's leg, preventing escape. Toothless variants exist, using clamping pressure alone to catch and hold prey.]
[What "pressure plate" means: A thin button-like plate that rests on the ground, sometimes hidden/camouflaged, which will activate various types of mechanisms and/or traps once pressure is applied.]
82.name: Hazards/Traps

83.content:
[What "arrow" means: The projectile launched by a bow, crossbow, or concealed trap. It has a sharp, weighty point and fletchings on the rear to stabilize its flight.]
[What "dart" means: A short-shafted ranged projectile with fletching. Commonly found in temples and dungeons, fired out of traps whenever triggered; often tipped with deadly poisons.]
[What "kunai / shuriken / throwing star" means: Traditional Japanese concealed weapon that was generally for throwing, and sometimes stabbing or slashing. They are sharpened hand-held blades, commonly depicted in popular culture as a multiple bladed (usually three or four) throwing weapon with a hole in the middle as a holding point. This weapon is commonly used by ninjas/shinobi/kunoichi, but can also be installed into traps.]
83.name: Hazards/Traps: Arrows/Darts/Projectiles

84.content:
[What "laser" means: A beam of energy meant to cut through and obliterate objects, or, at weaker levels, a harmless light meant to assist shooters in targeting. Some lasers may be deflected off of reflective objects.]
[What "laser hallway" means: A clichéd type of trap found in various action movie. As the name suggest, it is a hallway that is filled with several laser beams that should anyone came into contact with it, the trap will alert of their presence and/or triggering booby traps to kill the intruder; often dicing/chopping them apart on contact.]
[What "energy beam" means: A beam of energy fired as a weapon or magic attack. Similar to lasers, but can also be explosive or have other magical properties.]
84.name: Hazards/Traps: Beams/Lasers/Sci-fi

85.content:
[What "trap door" means: A door located either on the floor or the ceiling rather than the wall; a ceiling trap door typically leads to an attic, while a floor-based one leads to a basement or cellar. However, trap doors can lead to fatal locations/drops as well.]
[What "pitfall" means: A type of trap wherein the unsuspecting victim falls into a hidden hole in the ground, often covered by leaves or some such. May often have deadly spikes or sharpened punji sticks on the bottom.]
[What "cave pit / underground hole" means: A significantly vertical cave, shaft, or pothole which is open to the surface or found deep within horizontal caves. Among cavers, a pit is a vertical drop of any depth that cannot be negotiated safely without the use of ropes or ladders.]
[What "abyss / bottomless pit" means: An unfathomably deep or boundless place. The term could also refer literally to the depths of the sea, the deep source of a spring. or the interior of the Earth. Falling down this type of pit would mean certain death.]
85.name: Hazards/Traps: Cliffs/Pitfalls/Trap Doors

86.content:
[What "quicksand" means: A mix of sand and water on loose soil. Easy to sink in, hard to get out of. Mud can sometimes have the same effects as this.]
[What "tar" means: A black, oily, sticky, and viscous substance originally derived from organic materials (including coal). Victims may get stuck in this and never get out, especially if they are stupid.]
[What "glue trap" means: A type of trap consisting of a piece of cardboard or other backing material covered with a sticky adhesive layer. They are considered to be cruel and inhumane.]
86.name: Hazards/Traps: Glues/Liquids/Quicksand

87.content:
[What "molested / forced" means: Unwanted groping or being touched sexually by another, and/or being forced to do something against one's will.]
[What "non-con / rape" means: Nonconsensual penetration and other sexual acts on an unwilling victim who is often visibly unhappy, in pain, distressed, crying, or scared; sometimes ends with snuffing out the victim's life, depending on how violent the rapist/predator is. Rape especially applies to any/all victims that are considered slaves, prisoners, prey, captives, detainees, and/or sexual pets.]
[What "ryona / ryonage" means: A sub-genre of snuff/guro depicting women in extreme pain/bruising or being defeated and raped, with a particular focus on its sexualized depiction. May also end with the abused/raped victim being snuffed eventually and/or their corpse being defiled afterward. If being attacked by a monster, the woman's fate often involves tentacle rape and/or vore.]
87.name: Rape/Ryona

88.content: [What "erotic execution" means: When the act of 'executing' is portrayed/seen in a much more eroticized manner, with a heavy focus on sexual pleasure gained from having a victim be put to death; similar to ryona, guro, and snuff. Use of bondage is more prevalent, as well as the victim being stripped down naked, either partially or fully, and molested/raped just before their death. Gratification may also stem from seeing the dead victim urinate/deficate themselves afterward; a final signal of their ultimate demise, as well as seen as a form of submission.]
88.name: Rape/Ryona: Erotic Execution

89.content:
[What "drug usage / alcohol usage" means: The use of illicit drugs and/or alcohol in the context of sexual activities.]
[What "date rape" means: Form of rape which begins with some sort of romantic/sexual relationship between two parties. It is particularly prevalent on college campuses, and frequently involves consumption of alcohol or other date rape drugs.]
[What "somnophilia / sleep molestation" means: Paraphilia in which an individual becomes sexually aroused by a targetted person who is asleep, unconscious, or passed out from drugs; eventually leading to perverted misconduct with said target. May count as an act of rape, especially if purposefully drugged prior.]
89.name: Rape/Ryona: Drugging/Somnophilia

90.content:
[What "mind control" means: Whenever one character will mentally or supernaturally take control of another person's mind, thoughts, and/or body through psychic/hypnotic means by using supernatural/magical powers, potent drugs, or brainwashing.]
[What "hypnosis" means: A trancelike state in which a person becomes highly suggestible, and a form of mind control. Usually indicated by a swinging coin or pendulum being used to hypnotize the person, or a smartphone with a magical app. Since mid-2010s, depiction of a hypnosis app on a smartphone has also became increasingly common. This is usually a sexual fetish in which the victim is hypnotized/manipulated into performing sexual acts, tricking/forcing them into 'consent'; hypnotized prey may also willingly allow themselves to be captured and/or eaten by a hypnotizing predator.]
90.name: Rape/Ryona: Hypnosis/Mind Control

91.content:
[What "murder / snuff" means: The desire for seeing/causing an individual's death for personal entertainment and/or sexual pleasure; the death can be a result of being killed, committing suicide, or other fatal circumstances. This term originates from describing a candle wick that has, or will be, extinguished/ended; to 'snuff' someone means to end their life.]
[What "snuff films" means: An extreme sub-genre of hentai/pornographic content, where the death of the victim is recorded on camera for later enjoyment (or financial profit). The deaths are often premeditated with slow build-up, with the purpose of further sexual gratification and anticipation for the killer committing the snuffing and/or someone else who may view the film afterward.]
91.name: Rape/Ryona: Murdering/Snuffing

92.content:
[What "poison" means: Anything that is damaging and contaminating to an existence of an object, like living things. Can kill slowly or quickly. A popular method of killing for assassins and criminal organizations.]
[What "cyanide poisoning" means: A poisoning that results from exposure to any of a number of forms of cyanide. Symptoms include headache, dizziness, and vomiting which is then followed by foaming of the mouth, drooling, seizures, convulsions, cardiac arrest, orgasms/climaxing, and then instant death. Onset of symptoms usually occurs within a range of a few seconds to a few minutes.]
[What "potions" means: The act of using and/or receiving a bottled substance that has a physical or mental effect on the character receiving it; implies fantastical or unrealistic results.]
92.name: Rape/Ryona: Poisoning

93.content:
[What "malice aforethought / premeditation" means: The malice/unlawful intention and plan to carry out a crime, or murder, before setting out to do so.]
[What "unsuspecting" means: When a gullible victim is completely unaware of a fellow 'partner' or 'friend' who has actually been lying and hiding their true nature as an impostor, keeping the victim oblivious to their agenda/plan/motive that is not yet revealed; the premeditated desire to eventually rape and/or murder the poor victim. Once the time is right, the 'trap' will be sprung and the unsuspecting target will never know the truth until it is too late.]
93.name: Rape/Ryona: Pre-meditation

94.content:
[What "self-preservation / survival instincts" means: For all life, 'pain' and 'fear' are integral parts of survival. Pain motivates individuals to withdraw from damaging situations, to protect a damaged body part while it heals, and to avoid similar experiences in the future. Fear encourages the seeking of safety/shelter, and may also cause a release of adrenaline; increased strength and heightened senses. Self-preservation may also be interpreted figuratively, in regard to the coping mechanisms one needs to prevent emotional trauma from breaking the mind.]
[What "fear / pain" means: Refers to the incorporation of one or more character(s) having reason to be fearful during sexual (or nonsexual) encounters/conflicts. However, 'fear' and/or 'pain' can be used in favor of villains/predators who wish to gain, or maintain, control over their victims/prey and force them into actions they wouldn't normally participate in.]
[What "horror / terror" means: Scenarios consisting of deeply disturbing/traumatizing encounters, unsafe environments, or dangerous individuals; may often include aspects that are considered threatening, creepy, macabre, scary, haunting, unsettling, or even mind-breaking.]
94.name: Threats/Tricks:

95.content:
[What "disguising" means: If an impostor or spy wishes to conceal their indentity, one common practice is to change their visual appearances; various clothes, outfits, makeup, and/or haircuts.]
[What "skinwalking" means: If a skinwalker or other type of supernatural/alien being wishes to conceal their indentity, one common practice is to steal someone's skin/body in order to blend-in; likely after killing or eating the previous owner of said skin/body. Alternatively, sometimes shapeshifting/mimicry abilities could also be utilized without killing (depending).]
95.name: Threats/Tricks: Disguising/Skinwalking

96.content:
[What "breath play" means: Restriction of oxygen to heighten sexual arousal and orgasm; methods to achieve this include choking, strangulation, suffocation, hanging, and smothering.]
[What "gun play / weapon play" means: Expresses an interest in the incorporation of weaponry with sexual activities, such as knives, swords, guns, and various other armaments. Having a gun placed in one's mouth is a popular example, which increases feeling of danger and sexual arousal.]
[What "blade play / knife play / edge play" means: This involves using a knife blade to either psychologically induce an adrenaline rush by gliding a knife across the body, or with actual cutting.]
[What "pseudo-rape / pseudo-snuff" means: Heighten sexual arousal from a partner who pretends to resist and to struggle, before being overpowered while roleplaying themselves getting raped and/or snuffed.]
96.name: Threats/Tricks: Gunpointing/Thrill Seeking

97.content: [What "manipulation" means: The action of manipulating someone in a clever or unscrupulous way. Manipulators use devious means to exploit, control, or otherwise influence others to their advantage; typically through hypnosis/mind controlling, telling lies, giving threats, gaining friendships/relationships, gaslighting, utilizing ransoms/hostages/blackmailing, or simply being very kind, friendly, and charming to unsuspecting targets.]
97.name: Threats/Tricks: Manipulation/Misleading

98.content:
[What "vore" means: Someone getting eaten, swallowed/consumed whole, or absorbed by another creature/monster.]
[What "swallowing" means: The act of ingesting chewed food down the throat, into the stomach. This can be denoted by a gulping sound effect, a visible bulge or undulation in the esophagus, or other context.]
98.name: Vore

99.content:
[What "absorption" means: A type of vore that involves the victim being merged into the predator's body, and/or being dissolved by an anatomical fluid of the predator. This is often the scenario regarding slime monsters.]
[What "dissolving" means: When a character or object becomes incorporated into a liquid, or turns to smoke.]
99.name: Vore: Absorption/Dissolving

100.content:
[What "cannibalism" means: When a character is shown eating its own kind, such as a human eating another human.]
[What "cooked alive / boiled alive" means: Death by boiling is a method of execution in which a person is killed by being immersed in a boiling liquid. Due to the lengthy process, death by boiling is an extremely painful method of execution. Executions of this type were often carried out using a large vessel such as a cauldron or a sealed kettle filled with a liquid such as water, oil, tar, or tallow, and a hook and pulley system.]
100.name: Vore: Cannibalism/Cooked

101.content: [What "chewed / chomped" means: The prey character is chewed and/or eaten piece by piece, or otherwise physically mutilated by the act of being consumed; typically connotates hard vore.]
101.name: Vore: Chewed/Chomped

102.content:
[What "tentacle rape" means: Involves self-sentient tentacles, or a character/entity with tentacle-like appendages, forcing themselves onto victims/prey. Often implies multiple penetration, constriction, tentacle restrainment, and sometimes strangulation.]
[What "squeezing" means: Firmly pressing something soft or yielding, typically with one's fingers, hands, or other appendages.]
[What "coiling" means: The act of becoming entwined, held or hugged in the grasp of a long tail, coils of a snake, serpent, or other long-bodied creature.]
102.name: Vore: Coiled/Constriction/Squeezed

103.content: [What "digested" means: When a preyed-on victim is being digested in whatever fluid(s) are applicable; often stomach acids within a large predator. This process can either be extremely slow and painful or it can be terrifyingly instant, depending on how powerful/potent the acidity is.]
103.name: Vore: Digestion

104.content: [What "disposal / excretion" means: A predator engaging in a vore-related action in which their prey will be consumed/swallowed, digested, and eventually disposed as a pile of excreted feces, bones/skeleton, half-digested tissue, and/or leftover clothes/hair; implies a horrifying death to the prey, without any exception, unless they manage to escape the predator's body before digestion occurs.]
104.name: Vore: Disposal/Excretion

105.content: [What "draining / pruning" means: A type of vore that involves a creature sucking the blood and/or insides out of a living being, including bones in most extreme examples. The predator will use its mouth, a proboscis, or a special type of tail. After the procedure is finished, the dead victim will likely be reduced to a mummified-like corpse or a lump of wrinkly skin.]
105.name: Vore: Drained/Pruned/Sucked

106.content:
[What "tentacle rape / tendril rape" means: Involves self-sentient tentacles, or a character/entity with tentacle-like appendages, forcing themselves onto victims/prey. Often implies multiple penetration, constriction, tentacle restrainment, and sometimes strangulation.]
[What "all the way through" means: The act of a character being penetrated by an object, or tentacle, and having it extend out their other end; typically ass/vagina to mouth, vice versa, or other orifices in a less realistic fashion. Can be harmless, painful, and/or fatal depending on circumstances/contexts.]
106.name: Vore: Tendrils/Tentacles/Vines
